:QUOTE
Farmers built hay in summer heat on this. That is the only endorsement it needs.

:INFO
What Switchel Is
Switchel — also called haymaker's punch — is an American colonial drink made from water, apple cider vinegar, ginger, and a sweetener like molasses, honey, or maple syrup. It was the field drink of 18th and 19th century farm laborers during summer harvest. The vinegar provides electrolytes and mild acidity, the ginger gives warmth and digestive benefit, and the sweetener provides quick energy. No fermentation required — it comes together in minutes.

:COUNTER.half
2 Tablespoons
Raw apple cider vinegar per 16 oz water
|
:COUNTER.half
1 Tablespoon
Raw honey or molasses per serving — adjust to taste

:PATH
Combine the Base Ingredients
Whisk together vinegar, sweetener, and grated ginger in a pitcher.
|
:INFO
Combine the Base Ingredients
In a large pitcher, combine 2 tablespoons of raw apple cider vinegar, 1 tablespoon of raw honey or molasses, and 1 teaspoon of freshly grated ginger. Whisk until the honey is fully dissolved. Taste — it should be pleasantly tart and gently sweet. Adjust ratios to your preference before adding water.

:PATH
Add Cold Water and Adjust
Pour in 16 oz cold water, taste, and adjust acid and sweetness.
|
:INFO
Add Cold Water and Adjust
Pour 16 oz of cold water over the base and stir well. Taste and adjust: more vinegar for tartness, more honey for sweetness, more ginger for heat. Switchel is intentionally tangy — it should pucker slightly without being unpleasant. Serve over ice immediately or refrigerate. For a larger batch, scale the ratios by volume.

:CHECKLIST
Classic Switchel Ratio (per 16 oz)
[ ] 2 tbsp raw apple cider vinegar
[ ] 1 tbsp raw honey, maple syrup, or molasses
[ ] 1 tsp freshly grated ginger
[ ] 16 oz cold water
[ ] Ice for serving

:NOTE
Molasses vs. Honey vs. Maple Syrup
Molasses makes the most historically authentic switchel and adds iron and potassium. Honey makes a lighter, more floral version. Maple syrup is subtler and pairs well with additional lemon juice. Try all three across separate batches to find your preferred base.

:QUOTE
Two tablespoons of vinegar in water and you have replaced every neon sports drink in your fridge.

